note.ab:
The heron leaves the pond and ascends to the peaks of the trees;

the peacocks do the tāṇḍava dance and cry out on the play-mountain;

the many frogs make their rough sounds in the pond;

the cuckoos warble after ascending into the boughs of the mango tree.

In all directions, the path was thickly crowded with snakes;

the roads couldn’t be travelled because of those great poisonous serpents.

The torrents of water broke off the petals of the Pāṭala tree;

the geese in the mountains made a plaintive ‘oo’ sound.

Herds of cows ascended further into the forest to avoid the flies;

the groups of gopīs enjoyed their lord’s love, to their delight.

The whole realm of the earth, flushed green, was made fragrant by the kadamba;

every part of my body was racked all the more by the Bodiless God.

As I rolled around on my uncomfortable bed I felt inordinate pain;

I was pierced by the sounds that were coming from the swarms of bees;

I was kept awake the whole night, anxious, with eyes that never shut;

and not able to sleep, I made this vastuka, gāthā, and dohā.

note.p:
With fragrant resin they gave themselves tilakas on their foreheads;
	       they annointed their bodies with kuṅkum and sandal;
	       they walked around, taking purses (?) in their hands;
	       they sang divine and captivating songs;
	       they provided incense with great devotion to their elders
               in the cow-stalls and horse-stables.
	       When I saw that, I sunk into grief:
	       My desires were not fulfilled, friend.
